                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@Crash: I won&apos;t debate the &quot;poor man&quot; part :-) It&apos;s true that statistical measurement precision requires many samples, but there are two conflicting goals - measurement and problem location. I&apos;m focussing on the latter, for which you need precision of location, not precision of measure. So for example, there can be, mid-stack, a single function call A(); that accounts for 50% of time, but it can be in another large function B, along with many other calls to A() that are not costly. Precise summaries of function times can be a clue, but every other stack sample will pinpoint the problem.&lt;/span&gt;

